"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Hywel","type":"LAST","meanings":["A Welsh name. Some write the name Hoel, which they render 'lordly;' if so, it may come from huail, a vice-regent, regent. Arthur derives the surname Howell from Corn. -Brit, houl, the sun; and he adds, high, exalted.' But Hywel is rather from hywel, conspicuous."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gwrgenas ap Hywel was born about 1050, in Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Hywel Ap Ieuf, was -4 and his mother, Mali Verch Gruffydd, was -3. He married Margred ferch Rhys about 1097, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died about 1125, in Wales, at the age of 77."},"et":{"Abt 1050–about 1125":"umbes 1050–umbes 1125","1050–1125":"1050–1125","1084–1122":"1084–1122","1097–1197":"1097–1197","1124–Female":"1124–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1055–Male":"1055–Surnud","1055–Female":"1055–Surnud","10